<p>The state's northern latitude provides extended daylight hours during summer months, with some areas experiencing up to 16 hours of daylight in June. This extended daylight period helps offset the shorter winter days, creating more balanced year-round production than many other northern states. Additionally, solar panels operate more efficiently in cooler temperatures, and North Dakota's cold, clear winter days often produce excellent solar generation despite shorter daylight periods.</p>

<p>North Dakota's flat terrain and minimal shading obstacles make it ideal for solar installations, with most residential properties having excellent southern exposure. The state experiences approximately 200 sunny or partly sunny days per year, providing consistent solar generation throughout all seasons. Wind patterns also help keep panels clean and cool, further optimizing energy production efficiency.</p>

